======================================================================================================================
LOGIC / MATH BUGS — financial calculations
======================================================================================================================

[LOGIC] Provisions are accumulated in NATIVE currency but reported alongside default-currency totals
    Files: flaskr/analyzers/profits.py:144,168,182,197  flaskr/analyzers/period.py:115
           flaskr/pricing/pricing.py:334-347 (_getProvision)
    Every place that sums `operation.provision` does so WITHOUT applying `currencyConversion`.
    Inside the Profits analyzer:
        - _buy:   self._running.provision += operation.provision          (native)
        - _sell:  breakdown.provisions = operation.provision + running.partProvision(quantity)  (native)
        - Result: sum of breakdown.provisions + running.provision         (native)
    Period.profits.provisions does the same: `+= operation.provision`.
    HistoryPricing._getProvision accumulates native too.
    Meanwhile netProfit / netInvestment / value ARE converted to default currency on the same lines.
    Effect: for any USD/EUR/GBP asset, the displayed "provision" column is in foreign currency but
    rendered as if PLN. The per-portfolio "Net P/L" in wallet_historical.js subtracts these mixed
    numbers from PLN totals — all multi-currency portfolios show wrong P/L and wrong tax-relevant
    provision totals. Fix: multiply provision by currencyConversion at every accumulation point.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Profit is computed by AVERAGE COST while matchingOpenPositions is FIFO — inconsistency
    File: flaskr/analyzers/profits.py:191-216 (_sell)
    `breakdown.profit = operation.price - self._running.partPrice(quantity)` where
    `partPrice = self.price * quantity / self.quantity` is the running AVERAGE cost basis.
    But the loop right below it (lines 201-209) walks preceding breakdowns in chronological order
    and decrements `remainingOpenQuantity` FIFO, then exposes those matches in
    `matchingOpenPositions` (used by the results template to show which BUYs were closed).
    Worked example: BUY 10@100, BUY 5@150 (avg=$116.67), SELL 8@120.
        - avg-cost profit shown:  120*8 - 116.67*8 = +26.67
        - FIFO profit (what tax wants): closes 8 of first BUY -> 120*8 - 100*8 = +160
    The results page tells the user they sold their oldest 8 shares (FIFO matching) but charges
    them avg-cost P/L. For Polish Belka tax (FIFO is mandated), the per-operation profit number
    is wrong. Pick one method and use it consistently in both places.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Aggregating deposit accounts recomputes finalQuantity with wrong rule for EARNING ops
    File: flaskr/analyzers/aggregate.py:60-66
    Receipt.py stores deposit EARNING (interest) operations with finalQuantity computed using BUY
    semantics (typeForAdjustment = buy in receipt.py:133-134), so the stored finalQuantity for an
    interest payment includes the interest amount.
    When two deposit accounts are merged, _merge re-derives finalQuantity by calling
    `typing.Operation.adjustQuantity(operation['type'], finalQuantity, operation['quantity'])`
    using the STORED type 'EARNING'. But adjustQuantity for EARNING returns `initial` unchanged
    (typing.py:35-36). So interest payments do NOT add to the merged finalQuantity.
    Effect: a wallet showing merged deposit accounts undercounts the balance by the sum of all
    interest paid. Fix: pass an asset-type-aware override in _merge, or change EARNING semantics
    in adjustQuantity to depend on asset type.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] EARNING provisions are silently dropped when creating the billing operation
    File: flaskr/apps/assets/receipt.py:209-212
    The billing-side cash adjustment is computed as
        billingOperation['quantity'] = adjustQuantity(operation['type'], quantity, provision)
    where operation['type'] is the ORIGINAL op type. For BUY/SELL this correctly adds/subtracts
    provision. But for EARNING (e.g. a dividend with withholding tax recorded as provision)
    adjustQuantity returns the quantity unchanged (typing.py:35-36).
    Effect: a $100 dividend with $19 tax records a $100 inflow on the billing deposit instead of
    $81. The user's cash balance drifts upward by the tax amount every dividend.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Profits.matchOrders (FIFO by orderId) is never used by the Profits analyzer
    Files: flaskr/pricing/pricing.py:61-88 (matchOrders) vs flaskr/analyzers/profits.py:201
    `matchOrders` groups operations by `orderId` and does FIFO matching only within each group,
    and is consumed by Pricing._byInterest (parametrized assets) and HistoryPricing.
    The Profits analyzer uses a different scheme: chronological matching across ALL operations,
    ignoring orderId. Result: per-asset profit numbers, parametrized valuations, and historical
    pricing all use different conventions for what counts as an "open position." If `orderId` is
    supposed to mean anything (e.g. matching a specific SELL to specific BUYs from the same
    broker order), the Profits analyzer needs the same logic — or `orderId` should be deleted.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Period analyzer half-open vs results-page closed interval mismatch
    Files: flaskr/analyzers/period.py:77 vs flaskr/apps/results/index.py:98
    The Period analyzer treats operations with `op.date >= startDate AND op.date < finalDate` as
    in-scope. The results template loop in index.py uses `op.date <= timerange['periodEnd']`.
    For the CURRENT year, periodEnd = `min(Jan 1 next year, datetime.now())` — so an operation
    occurring at the exact `datetime.now()` boundary is shown in the operations table but is NOT
    included in the analyzer's netProfit/provisions totals. The totals row and the per-row totals
    won't reconcile on the current-year report at the moment a new operation is added.
    Use the same comparator on both sides (prefer `[startDate, finalDate)` everywhere).
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] _parseNumeric silently returns None on invalid input; callers store None into the DB
    File: flaskr/apps/assets/receipt.py:13-24, used at lines 126, 150, 154, 157
    On a non-numeric value (e.g. a comma in a locale-sensitive field or a pasted stray character),
    _parseNumeric returns None. The caller assigns None directly into the operation dict and the
    receipt POST proceeds. Downstream comparisons like `operation['finalQuantity'] < 0` raise
    TypeError, OR the operation gets persisted with quantity=None which corrupts every subsequent
    analyzer that calls .partPrice etc. Either raise ReceiptError on None, or validate at a single
    boundary with a proper response code.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] `assert quantity == Decimal(0)` in Profits._sell is a production crash, not a check
    File: flaskr/analyzers/profits.py:211
    If somehow there are not enough preceding open positions to close a SELL (data corruption,
    bad migration, manual DB edit), the analyzer triggers an AssertionError that kills the whole
    request — wallet, results, and assets pages all break at once. Replace with a proper
    exception that propagates to header.errors so the user sees which asset is bad and the rest
    of the portfolio still renders.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Aggregating assets changes the cost basis used for profit calculations
    File: flaskr/analyzers/aggregate.py + flaskr/apps/wallet/wallet.py:59
    When the wallet is requested with ?aggregation=p (or n), assets are merged and then Profits
    is run over the merged operations. Running average cost on the merged stream gives a
    different per-SELL profit than running Profits per-asset and summing. Example: two USD
    accounts at the same broker each with their own BUY 10@100 and BUY 10@200, then SELL 5 from
    one of them. Per-asset profit uses that account's avg cost; merged profit uses the combined
    avg. The aggregated wallet totals won't match the sum of the per-asset Results page values,
    with no indication to the user. Decide on one canonical view.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Categories.fillStrategy can produce negative or wrong "Others" when allocations overlap
    File: flaskr/analyzers/categories.py:27-41
    If two `assetType` entries both claim the same category (e.g. both list "USD Equities" at
    100%), `remainingShare` for that strategy bucket becomes -100, and the `othersValue` at
    line 39 silently subtracts that bucket's value from the Others total. There is no validation
    that strategy.assetTypes' categories sum to <= 100% per allocation key. Add a check or clamp.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Subcategory + category name concatenation is ambiguous
    Files: flaskr/analyzers/categories.py:24, flaskr/apps/wallet/static/wallet/strategyTable.js:88,
           flaskr/apps/wallet/static/wallet/wallet_historical.js:30
    Category bucket names are formed as `subcategory + ' ' + category`. Real-world names like
    subcategory="Mid Cap" + category="Equities" = "Mid Cap Equities" can collide with a single
    category named "Mid Cap Equities" or any subcategory whose tail matches another category's
    head. Use an unambiguous separator (e.g. ' / ') or a tuple key.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] HistoryPricing parametrized SELL assumes operations within an orderId are date-sorted
    File: flaskr/pricing/pricing.py:391-416
    Operations are iterated in the order MongoDB returns them inside each orderId bucket. There
    is no explicit sort by date. A SELL stored before its corresponding BUYs in the array would
    try to subtract from positions that haven't been appended yet, crashing on `opq[firstIdx]`.
    Either sort `operations` by `.date` at the top of `_priceAssetByInterest`, or assert order.
    Also: the SELL match loop (lines 410-416) never breaks when remainingQuantity reaches 0; it
    keeps iterating with min(0, x) = 0. O(N^2) on lots-heavy assets; add an early break.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Header.lastQuoteUpdate rendered without a None guard on `daysPast`
    File: flaskr/templates/base.html:49
    `{{ "green" if header.lastQuoteUpdate.daysPast < 3 else "red" }}` assumes daysPast is a
    number. If header.lastQuoteUpdate exists but daysPast is None/missing, the Jinja2 comparison
    raises TypeError and breaks the entire page render. Guard with an additional `is not none`.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIC] Period analyzer error path is set but downstream rendering not verified
    File: flaskr/analyzers/period.py:66-68 + flaskr/apps/results/index.py:92
    `if initialNetValue is None or finalNetValue is None: error = True; return`. The Result then
    has None for several Decimal fields. results/index.py:92 only skips assets where
    `period.profits.isZero()`, but an `error=True` asset with None fields is still pushed to
    `assetData`. The template will try to format None as currency and either show garbage or
    crash. Either drop error-tagged assets from the report, or render an explicit error row.
